check for equal variance assumption

We will test for equal variance assumption by: 1. checking for heteroscedasticity in the residual plot and the Scale Location plot 2. performing the Breusch-Pagan Test

#a scale location plot
ggplot(FinalModel, aes(x=.fitted, y=sqrt(abs(.stdresid)))) +
geom_point(colour = "purple") +
geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +

geom_smooth( colour = "green4")+
ggtitle("Scale-Location plot : Standardized Residual vs Fitted values")

From the plots above, there is no funneling in the residual plan and the scale location plot is relatively horizontal. This suggests that the residual plot is not heteroscedasicity. We perform further test below with the Breusch-Pagan Test to validate the equal variance assumption

We set up the following hypothesis

H0 : heteroscedasticity is not present (homoscedasticity)

Ho ${σ1}^2 = ${σ1}^2 =. . . = \({σn}^n\)

Ha :heteroscedasticity is present

Ha at least one σ is different from the others i = 1, 2, . . . , n

We carry out the test in R below

bptest(FinalModel)

    studentized Breusch-Pagan test

data:  FinalModel
BP = 394.53, df = 52, p-value < 2.2e-16

Since the p_value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and do have heteroscedascity in the model.

Test for Normality

We evaluate the normality assumption using the QQ plot and the shapiro’s test

#normal QQ plot
ggplot(LifeExpectancy, aes(sample=FinalModel$residuals)) +
stat_qq() +
stat_qq_line()
#optional histogram
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

Since the residual points are close to the normality line, this suggests that the data is normally distributed. The normality assumption is met.

We performed the Shapiro test to further assess the normality assumption based on the following hypotheses

Null hypothesis Ho: There is normality in the residual data

Alternative hypothesis Ha: There is no normality in the residual data

#Testing for Normality

shapiro.test(residuals(FinalModel))

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  residuals(FinalModel)
W = 0.99087, p-value = 1.501e-12

Since the p_value is less than 0.05, we fail reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is non normality.
